04693nam a22006255i 9780889207820DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061987xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892078207 a10.51644/97808892078202doi  a(DE-B1597)667794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a971.3/121 aHedican, Edward J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ogoki River Guides :bEmergent Leadership among the Northern Ojibwa /cEdward J. Hedican. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (186 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Maps and Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCollins: A Non-Reserve Indian Community -- tEconomic Incorporation and Exchange -- tEmergent Leadership and Economic Opportunity -- tORG and the Whitewater Project -- tConclusion -- tCollins Ten Years After -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Ogoki River Guides describes the prolonged struggle that members of a small native community in northern Ontario have undertaken in their attempt to establish a viable local economy. The leaders of Collins, the community in which the events of the book take place, have made a concerted effort to ensure that the community takes charge of its own affairs and in doing so have generated some important lessons for governmental policy in northern areas. The study makes evident the fact that certain changes in current government practices are needed, especially in areas of local inputs into policy and control issues, if community–based groups like Ogoki River Guides are to flourish and if real local initiatives in economic development has a chance to become a widespread pattern in northern areas. The suggestions, then, is that studies such as the present one which focus on the economic development projects of the native community are necessary in order to help orient government policy and planning. The author uses as exchange theory approach to study the conditions favouring emergent community leadership and to analyse the ways in which political activity in small communities is apt to change under particular conditions and stresses. Yet he also demonstrates some of the inadequacies of exchange theory itself, especially in terms of its difficulty in accounting for variations in historical and cultural change. The Ogoki River Guides should be of interest not only to those in the academic community, but also to those concerned with native affairs at the community level or in higher administrative capacities of planning, policy, and development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollins (Ont.)xEconomic conditions. 0aHistory. 0aIndian business enterprisesxOntarioxCollins. 0aIndian business enterpriseszOntariozCollins. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEconomic conditionsxOntarioxCollins. 0aIndians of North AmericazOntariozCollinsxEconomic conditions. 0aOgoki River Guides. 0aOjibwa IndiansxEconomic conditions. 0aOjibwa business enterprises. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920782040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207820/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a